&#xa0;
[normal]Written evidence submitted by[bold] WRAP (the Waste &amp; Resources [bold]Action Programme)[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Executive Summary[bold]1.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]WRAP welcomes the opportunity to provide written evidence to the Environmental Audit Committee’s Inquiry into 
[normal]the sustainability of measures to reduce the use of plastic shopping bags.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]WRAP is the UK governments’ delivery body for waste and resource efficiency issues. Further information on WRAP’s overall role and remit is at Annex 1. In relation to carrier bags, WRAP carries out four relevant activities:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]3.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]We hope that this evidence will be of use to the Committee, and would be happy to expand upon it further in oral evidence if that would be helpful.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Response to the Call for Evidence[bold]4.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The Committee’s call for evidence includes ten questions. We have responded to each of them in turn below.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Q1.[bold]              [bold]What will t[bold]he environmental impacts of the proposed 5p charge in England[bold] be?[bold]In particular, what will be: (a) t[bold]he likely change in the number of bags discarded and any benefits for b[bold]iodiversity and the environment?[bold] [bold](b) [bold]the likely change in the volume of plastic film produced, and the impact of a reduced demand for the oil producti[bold]on by-product used to make bags? And (c) [bold]the impact o[bold]f[bold] the use of biodegradable bags and the impact on plastics recycling[bold]?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Likely change in the number of bags discarded and any benefits for biodiversity and the environment
[normal]5.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Before going into detail on carrier bags, it is worth putting this issue into context. The UK generates around 28 million tonnes of household waste a year. Of this, 7 million tonnes (25%) is food waste and 5 million tonnes (17.5%) is packaging. 
[normal]Carrier bags account for less than 1% of household waste.[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]6.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]It takes plastic carrier bags a long time to degrade. While this can create problems and public concern in terms of litter, visual amenity and harm to wildlife if carrier bags are not disposed of responsibly, it does mean that the impact of the end of life phase on climate change is low, with the main impacts coming in the production stage. Given the low tonnage and the low degradation rate, the (non-litter) environmental impacts of actions related to plastic carrier bags are likely to be small, when compared to some other areas of waste and resource management (such as food waste prevention). Nonetheless, there is still the potential for some reduction in resource use.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]7.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Between 2006 and 2009, there was a voluntary Carrier Bag Agreement between the four governments across the UK and the British Retail Consortium and its supermarket members. The agreement had a target to reduce thin-gauge carrier bags by 50% by the spring of 2009 against a 2006 baseline through the use of voluntary measures taken by the supermarkets. This target was narrowly missed, with a 48% reduction measured for the UK. WRAP’s role under the agreement was to collect and analyse the data on carrier bag numbers, and to publish the figures.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]8.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]When th
[normal]e 
[normal]a
[normal]greement
[normal] came to an end in 2009
[normal], 
[normal]seven
[normal] major retailers agreed to continue monitoring carrier bag u
[normal]sage during 2010, 2011 and 2012,
[normal] although no formal target was agreed to measure against. The participating retailers were: Asda (including ex-Netto stores), Co-operative Group, Marks &amp; Spencer, Morrison’s, Sainsbury’s
[normal], Tesco and Waitrose. WRAP continued with its
[normal] role 
[normal]of data collection, analysis and publication.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]9.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]The most recent (2012) data was published by WRAP o
[normal]n 
[normal]18 
[normal]July 2013
[normal]. This
[normal] show
[normal]ed
[normal] that 
[normal]8.1 billion thin-gauge[bold] (single-use) bags[bold] were used by supermarke
[normal]t customers in the UK in 2012,
[normal] an increase of 1.3% compared with 2011 (8 billion), 
[normal]but
[normal] a decrease of 34% compared with 2006 (12.2 billion). 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]10.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]T
[normal]he 
[normal]total 
[normal]number of carrier bags (
[normal]both 
[normal]thin-gauge and 
[normal]‘
[normal]Bags for Life
[normal]’
[normal] 
[normal]) used by supermarket retailers in the UK 
[normal]in
[normal] 2012
[normal] increased by 1.1% to 8.5 billion bags
[normal]. 
[normal]In per capita terms, this equates to 10.7 bags per person per month in 2012, compared to 16.7 bags per person per month in the baseline year of 2006.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]11.
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]England, Scotland, and Northern Ireland all saw increases in thin-gauge carrier bag use between 2011 and 2012. Wales saw a reduction of 76%
[normal] over the year
[normal], 
[normal]which was the first full year since
[normal] the introduction of the 
[normal]five pence 
[normal]carrier bag charge in Wales
[normal] on 1 October 2011
[normal].
[normal] The data on the numbers of thin-gauge carrier bags used in each nation between 2010 and 2012 is presented in Table 1 below. In per capita terms, thin-gauge bag use per person per month ranged from a low of 1.8 in Wales to 11.8 in Scotland.
[normal]&#xa0;
